Testing.
This is October the 9th, sitting in the very pleasant office of Dennis Carrington, chatting with him about his experiences in what we used to call intramurals here at A&M.
Dennis, for the sake of someone who might read this material and not be acquainted with you, describe your experience before getting to A&M.
Where did you grow up?
What did mom and dad do?
Where did you go to college?
And what did you do before coming here?
I was born in Cherokee Island.
My dad was a rent farmer.
We lived on the farm until I think I was in sixth grade.
And at that time, he decided I went to work for a local company that sold and delivered fertilizer to farmers in that part of the country.
And at that time, moved to town.
That was really a big deal to live in town.
I spent the first several years of my life on the farm.
doing things farm kids do.
Of course, living in Quimby, Iowa, a town of about 400, wasn't much different than living in the country.
It was a very small town.
I grew up in a school district, small school district, very into sports.
Sports were very important to the kids that went to school there.
I always had good sports teams.
That was probably my, the direction that I was headed in was probably started there in that school district.
I started college at Iowa State University.
I thought I'd play basketball there.
Found out pretty quickly I wasn't quite good enough to play there.
And I actually got a half scholarship to Morningside College, my sophomore year.
Went there and played basketball on the freshman team that year.
I was married at the time and had a child.
I quit sports and started working my way through college.
I started playing intramurals, actually, after putting varsity basketball.
That was the first taste of intramurals, the first time I knew anything about intramurals.
My degree was in physical education.
At Morningside?
At Morningside College.
Morningside was about 1,200 students, probably, a Methodist-related school.
Very good place to go to school, good liberal arts education.
I had a degree in physical education, teaching certificate.
I was planning on teaching and actually a teaching job offered to me and I also had the opportunity to do a graduate assistantship at Iowa State.
At that point in time after doing my student teaching I decided maybe I'd be better off teaching in college than in high school.
So I went to Iowa State, spent a year there and I worked with Len Rady who was involved with then the National Intramural Association.
He was doing a presentation
in Los Angeles and asked me to help him with it.
So while I was there and doing the presentation, I met some people from Texas.
They offered me a graduate assistantship.
I spent four years at the University of Texas.
Came to Texas A&M.
How did you and Texas A&M link up?
Carl Landis was the
Carl Landis had called Sonny Rooker, who was the director of men's intramurals at the University of Texas, and asked him for a recommendation.
Actually, I just looked at some old files here recently.
There evidently was five people interviewed.
I only knew that I was interviewed.
There was actually five people interviewed for the job in the summer of 1973.
In June of 73.
job was offered to me in 1973.
But it primarily based on the recommendation of Sonny Berger and copies of the recommendation letter, a really outstanding letter.
Do you have any recollection of what they talked about or asked about in the interview?
What did it appear they were looking for?
Well, this is, I can't remember.
This was in 1973 in the state of San Am.
At that time, my hair was fairly long, about as long as it is right now, and I had a mustache.
Sonny, a good friend of mine, said, Dennis, you might want to cut your hair and shave your mustache before you get out there.
So I told him, Sonny, I'll cut my hair, but I don't want to shave my mustache.
So I cut my hair a little shorter because the...
He knew Carl Landis fairly well.
He knew Carl was fairly conservative.
And he was right.
But even though my hair was a little long, Carl did hire me.
We talked about what an opportunity there was at this university.
The intramural program had been almost entirely core.
Of course, the university was almost entirely core up until, you know, the late 70s probably.
So there was, with women being fully admitted around 72, this really opened up the opportunity for an intramural program to expand and grow.
It really created an opportunity to explore a lot of different possibilities.
The good thing about the way it developed at Texas A&M, most of their schools at the universities at that time had a men's program and a women's program.
Totally segregated.
That didn't happen here because there weren't women here.
It didn't happen until the early 70s.
So we started basically with a program for everybody, men, women, and that allowed us to offer men's and women's programs from the same department.
It allowed us to offer co-rec programs from the same department.
Most of the universities had either two or three departments.
Some of them had a men's program, a women's program, and a co-rec program.
from my three different administrations.
So we bypassed all that stuff, and we're pretty lucky because of the way things had developed here.

And the women's program just kind of flowed with the rest of it, and there weren't the kind of the, you know, for a university that was all male, all of a sudden, the program looked a lot better than most places where they had been segregated for years.
Were you replacing anyone?
Actually, Carl Landis had put Les Palmer in the director's job, and Les did a lot of teaching in the kinesiology program, the physical education program.
He's a great bowling instructor, he's a former baseball player, he taught a lot of different things over there, but bowling was probably his favorite.

less wanted to go back to teaching carl placed him in the director's job to try to bring the program back up to to carl's standards it evidently slipped a little bit a few years before that and less wanted to go back to teach so that's what carl decided to take a look and see if he could find somebody
And what they were looking for was somebody as young as me to take a program that was in pretty good shape and really move it forward.
And that's kind of what we talked about in that interview.
What was your title as you began?
Your title?
Director Venimeros.
Director Venimeros.
And you reported to?
Arlandis.
In the department of?
Which was in the College of Education.
So it was theoretically then, organizationally, it was an academically related.
It was.
The only difference that, the good difference,
in this university is the money was coming from student fees.
The student service fee was funding the program.
So the nice thing about that is we weren't competing for academic money in a program that was not academically related.
We were competing for student service money in the student service program and that was a good part of it.
It just so happened that we reported through an
And for many years, probably until sometime in the 80s, all of us or some of us taught in physical education.
And your beginning salary?
$12,000 in service fees and $600 for teaching, because I was teaching six, I think.
And this is the fall of 73?
Fall of 73.
Fall of 73.
What facilities, what spaces did intramurals have?
We were officed in DeWare Field House.

There was a, at that time there was like a central office and that's where we had a full-time secretary, we had some student workers that worked there and kind of a counter set up to take entries and do all that business.
There was actually an office behind that area that we used more for storage at that time.
And then there was an office for the assistant director, an office for the director that's probably three times as big as my current office.
It was huge.
And then we had another office where we had equipment checkout and rental that serviced the DeWare facility.
DeWare itself at that time was one big gymnasium.
It had been remodeled at some point in time in the 60s.
There was 14 handball courts on the upper level.
They put in a second level, lowered the ceiling height in the old field house, and then put 14 handball courts up there.
There was also a weight room that belonged to the athletic department.
It was about 3,000 square foot.
And we used that weight room for recreation
There was also a men's locker room, another small storage room that we ended up using for an office.
As we grew, we needed office space.
And a very small women's restroom.
There was no women's shower facilities on campus at that time.
This budget of $50,000, that paid salaries.
Salaries were full-time.
pay wages for student workers are officials primarily.
That's.
All so you have to pay for the use of any space.
What what for space to go use.
At that time we had.
probably a softball field.
Every green space on campus had a softball field.
None of them at that time were lighted.
The area just south of Kyle Field had an astroturf racing field that we used that.
And the area, the new, what is now the older of the tennis courts,
football practice fields in that area.
So we had just south of Kyle Field, four practice fields.
Or four, three or four that we used.
And over on Duncan Drill Field, which at that time was a side of the Bonfire, we used that until the middle of October.
And we probably had eight football fields there at one time.
We also had an arrangement where we had about eight softball fields in the spring.
We had

other spaces uh what's now called peakly beach and there we had two softball fields and we could actually put in two ball fields since the drill field was a drill field back then but we used it primarily for sports clubs and even
or any activity that was forbidden in a certain place in the intramural?
No.
In fact, we used Kyle Field from time to time.
We didn't use it for games.
If we needed lights, if we started running out of space and time to run programs, yeah.
That's a good point.
When you started out, did anybody give you any advice?
Do's or don'ts?
If so, summarize that.
Carl Landis, Les Palmer, John Corliss, anybody?
No, not really.
As a matter of fact, I can recall writing a memo to Carl Landis that had three or four things that I thought we ought to do at some point.
And I was ready to
I'm not sure if I said it specifically, but I was really thinking at the start of the next year that we ought to consider doing some of these things and within a month he said let's start.
Either all of them or most of them right now, he was ready to go.

So to some degree they were looking for somebody that had brought some experience from someplace else and as young as I was, I did have some pretty good experience because Texas probably had the best program in the country at that time.
Did the fact that you had come from the University of Texas, did anybody tease you about it?
All the time.
All the time.
And probably one of the better stories, Rooster Andrews is still alive.
He's still over in Austin.
And he was, he's a sporting goods salesman.
And he sells to schools.
And he's got a huge connection with the University of Texas.
And we had always purchased stuff from him.
His going away present to me was about four or five different outfits.
And they're all burnt orange.
Although I never wore them on campus.
I wore them quite a bit when I was jogging around town and stuff like that.
But that was a pretty good story.
It wasn't until I sent two kids to Texas A&M that they finally let me be an Aggie.
Did anybody seriously ever say anything about your being from UT?
No.
I think everybody's always understood UT's a great school.
And the nice thing that we can say now that Texas A&M is just as good.
We've made a lot of progress over the years.
We were probably better than we thought we were back then, too.
At December, I think we had a little bit of an inferiority complex.
We had a great school back then, too.
And now we know it's not a problem anymore.
I try to work that into almost every speech I make about A&M.
And I try to do it at first and see the crowd with their eyes blank.
And then I try to say, don't you agree with me that everything they do, we try to outdo them?
And says yes.
And I said, and so therefore, we're both a lot
than we would be if the other one didn't exist.
Exactly.
With this recreation facility, Tom and I have worked together to make sure we can get our administration.
We are competitive.
We're still competitive.
Right.
As a newcomer, describe moving into station.
Are you living in what it was like to go to a new place?
Well, when I came down here for my interview, I really was.
And I lived in Boston for four years.
I had no clue where College Station was.
I made it to College Station one day and I didn't pull my map out when I got ready to leave.
I got lost leaving town.
Very good, very good.
So I finally I got somewhere in North Bryan and I was not on the right track and I had to pull the map out and figure out where I was and I finally made it back to Austin.
I moved into College Station.
I lived in a duplex just off of Southwest Parkway and in 1973 Southwest Parkway was the start of
of the country.
Nothing or almost nothing south of Southwest Parkway.
There was a few houses, but very few.
That whole area just has exploded with growth, and of course, the city at that time was 35,000.
The stories were, and they probably were true, there was two places where you could go get a beer in College Station in 1973.
a peanut shack on Auburn Road, and the other one was Sparky's Pizza over at Eastgate.
And I guess that was true.
I can't remember any other places at that time where alcoholic beverages were served at College Station.
There's a few others in Bryan, but that was a long way away.
Most people lived at College Station at that time.
But it was a very small town, about 35,000, very pleasant place to be.
The school district was great for my kids, and so all of that was just
positive as it could be.
And the sports programs in this town for kids was probably the best I'd ever seen.
All right, back on the campus, what were your goals as you started out?
The, besides DeWare Fieldhouse, at that time we had, she brought Dwight, which primarily
There was an addition to G. Raleigh White that had three basketball courts and a large locker room for men.
Another addition to G. Raleigh White, and they called it the expansion, they had one large basketball court and a dance room and an activity room, another classroom on the second floor.
And on the main floor, the primary reason the facility was built, it had a women's locker room.
It was the first women's locker room for physical activity classes on campus ever.
And that was the primary reason the facility was built.
In looking at the facilities that we had, it was evident to me coming from the University of Texas that we were behind in facilities.
Even at that time, I had a vision of building a reparation facility.
It took me about 22 years to get it done, but we did get it done.
And part of the reason it took so much time, in the late 70s, this university was growing by as much as 3,000 students every year, and trying to keep pace with
providing enough activity space for students to take classes.
The primary focus at that time was building enough activity space.
So most of the growth went through physical education.
We were designing physical education space as opposed to recreation space.
And there is a small difference
and what you can accomplish if you set out to design recreation space versus physical education space.
And that's why it took quite some time to really get around to building recreation space.
Were there any notable absences in our facilities, our capabilities, when you arrived?
Actually, we were able to accomplish everything we wanted to.
Probably the biggest drawback we had is the space in G. Riley White that wasn't air conditioned.
But most campuses at that time had similar situations.
We all know now, in today's time, that exercising in a space that's not air conditioned in the summer in Texas is very high risk.
Back then it was, you weren't banned unless you could do that.
We know better than that now.
That was probably the only thing.
We had the right kinds of things, we didn't necessarily have enough.
And of course that was a problem because the university went in 1973 from 18,600.
In 1985 we were, or 87 when we voted to build the rec center, we were about 35,000.
Pretty fast growth.
We're just trying to keep up with it, especially when teaching physical education activity classes.

is it appropriate for me to identify the different activities as sports what if so describe all the sports that were being uh conducted in intramurals when you got here for men and then for women we i would probably have to pull out some old which i don't think i have in my office here we were
At that time, we had four major sports volleyball, softball, like football and basketball.
Plus, track meet in the swimming, and they were they were huge.
We had 1000 people in the track meeting and probably 600 in the swimming back at that time.
And there were also some other sports like tennis,
handball, racquetball, some of what you consider individual and dual sports.
I would think we had probably ran about 30 tournaments the first year I was here in those sports.
And they were really focused on the core.
We had teams for leagues for core.
We had leagues for core freshmen.
We had independent leagues, and we had residence hall leagues.
Shortly, within the next two years, we opened that up.
to co-rec leagues and women's leagues.
And in the women's we had independent leagues and we had residence hall leagues.
Women's residence halls were started by that time.
What does co-rec mean?
Co-rec is where men and women play on the same team.
Such as?
They play just about everything we do.
Football, basketball, volleyball, softball, soccer, just about everything that we do.
And the key there is writing rules
that equalized the competition.
And the co-rec is really a lot more popular than our women's league.
We have more women playing in co-rec leagues than we do women's leagues.
Now we're in the neighborhood of 80 tournaments a year.
So we're down from 30 to 80.
But the big change that happened was women's leagues, co-rec leagues, and we went from offering one skill level
up to as many as four different skill levels.
What we're saying is we understand that there's people on this campus who play varsity and probably could play varsity for some colleges that are playing flag football.
There's also people like me that still want to play flag football, but I'd rather not play against

somebody that's that competitive so i play in class d if i play and those and class d is interesting in class c because you have people from 18 to 60 playing in those leagues and really enjoying it what we what we're trying to accomplish is an opportunity for everybody everybody to play in a competitive sport that match their interest in competition but not everybody wants to to
go out there and get hurt playing against high level competition.
Who encouraged the women to become more active in intramurals?
Did you and others?
Where did the drive come from?
In reality, most of that came from the men that played in the programs.
And that's why the co-reg leagues were so popular.
It was another opportunity for men to participate in competitive sports.
Even men coach, in reality, men coach most of the co-rec league teams, and men coach most of the women's.
Now these are student men?
Yeah.
So you'll have somebody from one of the men's residence halls, and he'll be coaching a men's team, then he'll get the co-rec team organized, and he'll coach them.
And then he may even coach at, he may be paired with one of the women's dorm residence halls on campus, and he may coach their women's team too.
Now in the 70s, was that already going on?
Yeah, it really got started in 74, 75 is when it really got going.
All right, our first women's dorm was January of 71 when Dr. Williams arrived, so it's that fast.
As you were getting started here,
Are there some people outside of the Department of Physical Education and the College of Education, are there some other people who were good allies?
Yes, very much so.
John Coles, Vice President for Student Services.
It was shortly, probably in 75 or 76, I started going to his staff meetings.
And I talked with Carl Landis, and I said, look, we're being funded by Student Affairs, Student Services.
John has this meeting, and he's invited me.
It'd probably make a lot of sense for me to be there from a funding point of view.
The better he knows us, the more likely he is to fund us.
And Carl Landis agreed with that.
And of course, they and I started almost a 20-year relationship with Dr. Gold.
He was very helpful to us along the way.

charles mccandless charles mccandless was the director of intramurals in the early 60s when i knew him he was associate vice president and he had responsibilities for facilities on this campus facility planning for the campus and he was always very helpful at a time when when we and physical education were growing so fast
and needing space so badly, he was there to champion our cause.
He understood us.
He understood what we were doing.
He was really helpful in that area.
Describe the personalities of Landis and Colas and McCandless.
Carl Landis and I are probably quite different.
I'm a lot more liberal than he is.
He's a lot more conservative than I am in a lot of ways, but
In time, and it didn't take very long time, we were probably best of friends.
Not only was he a good supervisor, a good boss, but we became good friends.
Just a great gentleman.
I can remember one time I got a little frustrated in a discussion with him and one of those words came out and he said, we don't do that in this office.
And I knew that and I knew from then on that I didn't become frustrated with him because
With Carl, it didn't.
If you had passion and presented a good argument, he was going to listen and he was going to give you an opportunity to prove yourself right or wrong.
I'm going to make believe that I'm a neophyte.
Could you count on Carl Landis to keep his word?
100% of the time.
110% of the time.
He's a great gentleman.
I think that's why I really appreciate him about as much as anybody I've known.
Describe the personality of Colas.
John Colas was...
probably for A&M and for the profession, an integrator in student affairs.
It's interesting because he came from physical education, so he understood our business pretty well.
He came from physical education, got started in student affairs at East Texas State, now Texas A&M Commerce.
So his PhD's in physical education, but he had a
a sense and a feeling for our students.
